  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div xml:id="AN155.2-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ piriviṉkaṇ vēṟupaṭṭa talaimakaḷ [colliyatu].</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What SHE said who had undergone changes during the separation from HIM.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN155.2">
            <lg type="edition">
              <l>aṟaṉ<supplied>kaṭai</supplied>p paṭāa vāḻkkaiyu meṉṟum</l>
              <l>piṟaṉkaṭaic cellāc celvamu miraṇṭum</l>
              <l>poruḷi ṉākum puṉaiyiḻai yeṉṟunam</l>
              <l>miruḷē raimpā ṉīvi yōrē</l>
              <l>nōynā muḻakkuva māyiṉun tāntañ</l>
              <l>ceyviṉai muṭikka tōḻi palvayiṟ</l>
              <l>payanirai cērnta pāḻnāṭ ṭāṅka</l>
              <l>ṇeṭuviḻik kōvalar kūvaṟ ṟōṇṭiya</l>
              <l>koṭuvāy pat<supplied>tal</supplied> vārntuku ciṟukuḻi</l>
              <l>nīrkāy varuttamoṭu cērviṭam peṟātu</l>
              <l>peruṅkaḷiṟu mititta vaṭikayat tirumpuli</l>
              <l>yotuṅkuvaṉa kaḻinta cetumpa līrvaḻic</l>
              <l>ceyirtīr nāviṉ vayiriyar piṉṟai</l>
              <l>maṇṇār muḻaviṉ kaṇṇakat tacaitta</l>
              <l>viralūṉṟu vaṭuviṟ ṟōṉṟi</l>
              <l>maralivāṭu maruṅkiṉ malaiyiṟan tōrē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>The one who stroked our [hair in] five parts, like the dark, (4)</l>
                <l>saying “two things, [namely] living that is not beneath [one’s] duty</l>
                <l>and prosperity that does not go to another’s door</l>
                <l>will be [possible only] by wealth, [you with] decorative jewels,” (1-3)</l>
                <l>even though we shall bear the pain, (5a-c)</l>
                <l>let him complete his work to be done, friend, (5d-6a-c)</l>
                <l>– he who has gone to traverse the mountains through places where the bowstring hemp fades, (16)</l>
                <l>in that place of ruined lands that [used to be] joined by [milk-]yielding herds on many sides, (7)</l>
                <l>as [the traces] on the moist way in the muddy land passed by dark tigers stepping</l>
                <l>into the depth of the foot [prints] that were trampled by the big elephant bull (11f.)</l>
                <l>without reaching a [watering] place, with hot suffering for the water (10)</l>
                <l>in the small pits into which the buckets with curved mouths overflow [and] shed [water] (9)</l>
                <l>when the long [time] vigilant cowherds dug out wells, (8)</l>
                <l>appear like the scars rising on the fingers (15)</l>
                <l>that beat right on the eye of the drum full of paste (14)</l>
                <l>behind dancers with blemishless tongues. (13)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
